   <abstract>Some of the most well-known illuminated manuscript marginalia come from the 14th-century Luttrell Psalter. Along with imaginative grotesques and working peasants, the Psalter includes depictions of non-English foreigners who would have been perceived as enemies by the book's patron, Sir Geoffrey Luttrell. These foreign "others" have taken a back seat to the informative images of English medieval life in the scholarship surrounding the Psalter. This thesis explores the use of racially composite "others" who embodied the believed immorality of several different groups including the Scots, Jews, and Muslims. The ambiguity of these figures allows for interpretation by both medieval and modern readers, highlighting the enduring impact of visual imagery in shaping and reinforcing societal attitudes. The hybrid "others" served as an antithesis to the ideal English Christian, generalizing "them" to more clearly define "us." Selective scratching and rubbing of multiple "others" suggest that readers understood the artists' visual language and actively fought these invented enemies. Alternatively, medieval literature suggests racial "others" may have served as reminders of the unsaved to a liturgical audience. This thesis argues that the Luttrell Psalter's ambiguous constructions allowed readers to readily identify certain figures as geographic and religious outsiders, allowing them to decide whether to approach the figures with disdain or empathy.</abstract>
